@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEProtXprlib1to20" "Xpr library 1 - 20"


                  @{b}SystemEditor (Protocols): Xpr library 1 - 20
                 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

Enter here 1 to 20 different Xpr-libraries.

You can also use the popup gadget to select the Xpr-libraries.


Examples and the first time from the SystemEditor generated:

 1: xprzmodem.library
 2:


Note: The first free gadget indicates the end of the available Xpr-libraries.
      In this case 2 is free so FAME uses only the first Xpr-library.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEProtUserBlkSize" "User Block Size"


                   @{b}SystemEditor (Protocols): User Block Size
                  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

Enable/Disable the posibillity for the users to choose their own
Xpr-Block-Size.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEProtDefIOBuffer" "Def. I/O Buffer"


                   @{b}SystemEditor (Protocols): Def. I/O Buffer
                  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

Following Xpr I/O Buffers are available:

 - 1K (1024 Bytes)
 - 2K (2048 Bytes)
 - 4K (4096 Bytes)
 - 8K (8192 Bytes)
 - 16K (16384 Bytes)          <- default
 - 32K (32768 Bytes)
 - 64K (65536 Bytes)
 - 128K (131072 Bytes)
 - 256K (262144 Bytes)
 - 512K (524288 Bytes)
 - 1M (1048576 Bytes)

The I/O Buffer is used by the Xpr-library and can speed up file transfers.

Note: Do not use one of the highest buffers, because you may think it
      must speed up transfers. That's not in every case correct !

      Use 16K or 32K, but not more if you don't know what you are doing,
      because this buffer must harmonize with your hard-disk transfer
      size else you will have an interupted transfer which is slower.

      If you want to check out what's the best one try transfering files
      with higher buffers and decrease it if transfer is interupted.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEProtDefBlksize" "Def. Blocksize"


                    @{b}SystemEditor (Protocols): Def. Blocksize
                   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

Following Default Blocksizes are available:

 - 64 Bytes
 - 128 Bytes
 - 256 Bytes
 - 512 Bytes
 - 1K (1024 Bytes)            <- default and strictly recommended !
 - 2K (2048 Bytes)
 - 4K (4096 Bytes)
 - 8K (8192 Bytes)

The Default Blocksize is used by the Xpr-library and can speed up file
transfers.

The Blocksize indicates the block size used to transfer datas via
Xpr-protocols. If the Blocksize is higher more datas per block and
less checksums will be transfered what results in a higher CPS.

Note: Highest Blocksizes musn't be the best and resulting in higher
      CPS rates. Only if your line is very good and stable you will
      have a higher CPS. If your line is bad you will have less CPS
      as with default 1K.

Note: The receiver and sender must have the same Blocksize set !!!

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "SEProtMaxUserBlksize" "Max User Blocksize"


                  @{b}SystemEditor (Protocols): Max User Blocksize
                 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

Following Max User Blocksizes are available:

 - 64 Bytes
 - 128 Bytes
 - 256 Bytes
 - 512 Bytes
 - 1K (1024 Bytes)
 - 2K (2048 Bytes)
 - 4K (4096 Bytes)
 - 8K (8192 Bytes)            <- default

The Max User Blocksize indicates the highest Blocksize a user can configure
and is used by the Xpr-library and can speed up file transfers.

If @{"User Block Size" link "SEProtUserBlkSize"} is enabled users can select and use their own
Block Sizes.

The Blocksize indicates the block size used to transfer datas via
Xpr-protocols. If the Blocksize is higher more datas per block and
less checksums will be transfered what results in a higher CPS.

Note: Highest Blocksizes musn't be the best and resulting in higher
      CPS rates. Only if your line is very good and stable you will
      have a higher CPS. If your line is bad you will have less CPS
      as with default 1K.

Note: The receiver and sender must have the same Blocksize set !!!

@endnode

